And I‚Äôve got to say, Jodi Picoult really knows how to weave a story together. This one tackles the controversial debate between pro-life and pro-choice, but doesn‚Äôt come across as preachy, or like the book is promoting a particular side. 

The book did introduce a number of characters right at the start, so it was quite hard to get them straight in my head. I didn‚Äôt actually think I was connecting with the characters and then suddenly I Was Hooked. The same thing happened with Nineteen Minutes when I read that back in February! Maybe it‚Äôs just that I take a while to connect to Picoult‚Äôs characters - suppose I‚Äôll have to read a third book of hers to find out üòÇ.

The only thing about this book that I wasn‚Äôt really convinced by was the narrative being told in reverse. For me it undercut a lot of the tension since you already knew what was going to happen ahead of time. It was really well done though, and the characters were amazingly managed and it was really interesting to see the character development in reverse!

